      <bioghist id="aspace_d52bbb4869de8bb52da331ab6caa8e2d">
         <head>James C. Scott</head>
         <p>James Campbell Scott (1936-2024) PhD '67 was a political scientist, anthropologist, and author. His areas of research included political economics, comparative agrarian societies, theories of resistance, peasant politics, the Southeast Asia region, and anarchism.</p>
         <p>Born in Mount Molly, New Jersey, Scott earned a bachelor's degree from Williams College in 1958 and a PhD in political science from Yale University in 1967. He earned a Rotary International Fellowship after graduating from Williams and studied in Myanmar where he became involved in local student politics.</p>
         <p>Scott was recruited by the Central Intelligence Agency to write reports about the students' anti-communist activities and later took a post in the Paris office of the National Student Association. He returned to the United States and started his academic career focusing on the politics of peasants, resistance, and anarchism.</p>
         <p>He taught at the University of Wisconsin-Madison and then moved to Yale University in 1976 where he enventually received tenure. He became the Sterling Professor of Anthropology, emeritus professor of anthropology, and co-founded the Agrarian Studies Program.</p>
         <p>Scott died in 2024.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <prefercite id="aspace_aaae3394a4520f464893ecd41f091db0">
         <head>Preferred Citation</head>
         <p>James C. Scott papers. General Collection, Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Yale University.</p>
      </prefercite>
      <processinfo id="aspace_daf2b5ed06125e02c0088159184c8423">
         <head>Processing Information</head>
         <p>Collections are processed to a variety of levels, depending on the work necessary to make them usable, their perceived research value, the availability of staff, competing priorities, and whether or not further accruals are expected. The library attempts to provide a basic level of preservation and access for all collections, and does more extensive processing of higher priority collections as time and resources permit.</p>
         <p>These materials have been arranged and described according to national and local standards. For more information, please refer to the Yale Archival Processing Manual.</p>
      </processinfo>
      <scopecontent id="aspace_8f6c81407ecd6387f5b727a1d7bf1e81">
         <head>Scope and Contents</head>
         <p>This collection contains research and field notes related to James C. Scott's professional work as a political scientist and anthropologist. The materials include subject files related to Southeast Asia from the 1970s and 1980s, which contain clippings, notes, course materials, and annotated bibliographies used in Scott's research process.</p>
         <p>Also included in this collection are forty notebooks from Scott's fieldwork in Kedah, Malaysia that span from 1978 to 1980, which resulted in one of his best-known books, "Weapons of the Weak: Everyday Forms of Peasant Resistance," published in 1985.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      <userestrict id="aspace_c65e5250277b25e604b5835633ab81e2">
         <head>Conditions Governing Use</head>
         <p>The James C. Scott papers is the physical property of the Beinecke Rare Book and Manuscript Library, Yale University. Literary rights, including copyright, belong to the authors or their legal heirs and assigns. For further information, consult the appropriate curator.</p>
      </userestrict>
